NOTICE — Anti-Fabrication Rider

This NOTICE supplements, but does not modify, the MIT License above.

1. Permitted Use. The Software is licensed solely to construct, stage, and
   transmit chargeback-evidence payloads that the Licensee has independently
   collected, retained, and verified as truthful and accurate as of the date
   of submission. Use of the Software to construct, stage, or transmit
   evidence that the Licensee knows or has reason to believe is false,
   fabricated, materially misleading, or generated by a large language model
   or other generative system is outside the scope of this license and
   immediately terminates all rights granted hereunder.

2. No Inducement. Pursuant to the standard articulated in MGM Studios, Inc.
   v. Grokster, Ltd., 545 U.S. 913 (2005), the Licensor expressly disclaims
   any purpose, intent, or design to induce, encourage, or facilitate the
   submission of false, fabricated, or materially misleading evidence to any
   acquirer, payment processor, card network, issuing bank, arbitrator, or
   regulator. The Software is designed and instrumented (see typed-evidence
   schemas at lib/evidence/schemas.ts and the CI guards at
   .github/workflows/ci.yml) to refuse uncategorized text, freeform
   narrative, and LLM-generated content.

3. Indemnity in favor of Licensor. To the maximum extent permitted by
   applicable law, the Licensee agrees to indemnify, defend, and hold
   harmless Dunecrest Ventures Inc., its officers, directors, employees,
   contractors, and successors and assigns (collectively, "Licensor
   Indemnitees") from and against any and all third-party claims,
   investigations, demands, losses, liabilities, fines, penalties, damages,
   and expenses (including reasonable attorneys' fees) arising out of or
   relating to: (a) Licensee's submission of evidence assembled, staged, or
   transmitted using the Software; (b) Licensee's violation of any card
   network rule, acquirer agreement, applicable consumer-protection statute,
   18 U.S.C. § 1343, or analogous foreign law; and (c) Licensee's processing
   of personal data using the Software, including without limitation under
   Regulation (EU) 2016/679 (GDPR), the UK GDPR, the California Consumer
   Privacy Act as amended by the CPRA, and Panama Law 81 of 26 March 2019.

4. No Representation of Outcomes. Nothing in the Software, this NOTICE, or
   any accompanying documentation constitutes a representation, warranty, or
   guarantee that any dispute will be qualified for Visa Compelling Evidence
   3.0 liability shift, accepted by Stripe, accepted by any issuing bank, or
   resolved in favor of the Licensee. Outcomes under the Visa Core Rules and
   the Stripe Disputes API are determined by parties other than the Licensor.

